  "prompt": "Does every dog has rabies?",
  "response": "No, not every dog has rabies. In fact, the vast majority of dogs worldwide do **not** have rabies, thanks to effective prevention measures such as vaccination and responsible pet ownership. Here's a more detailed overview:\n\n### **What Is Rabies?**\nRabies is a fatal viral disease that primarily affects mammals, including dogs and humans. The virus attacks the central nervous system, leading to severe neurological symptoms and, ultimately, death if not treated promptly after exposure.\n\n### **Transmission**\nRabies is typically transmitted through the saliva of an infected animal, most commonly via bites. It can also be spread if the saliva comes into contact with mucous membranes or open wounds.\n\n### **Vaccination and Prevention**\n- **Vaccination:** Vaccinating dogs against rabies is the most effective way to prevent the disease. In many countries, rabies vaccination for pets is not only recommended but often required by law.\n- **Control Programs:** Public health initiatives, such as animal control and vaccination campaigns, significantly reduce the incidence of rabies in dog populations.\n- **Monitoring and Quarantine:** Stray or wild animals suspected of having rabies are often captured and observed or tested to prevent the spread of the disease.\n\n### **Global Perspective**\n- **Developed Countries:** In regions with robust vaccination programs and animal control measures, rabies in dogs is relatively rare.\n- **Developing Countries:** Rabies remains a significant public health issue in some areas where vaccination and control measures are less accessible or rigorously enforced.\n\n### **Signs of Rabies in Dogs**\nA dog infected with rabies may exhibit symptoms such as:\n- Behavioral changes (aggression, fearfulness)\n- Excessive drooling or foaming at the mouth\n- Difficulty swallowing\n- Paralysis\n- Seizures\n\nHowever, these symptoms appear only after the virus has entered the nervous system, making early detection and prevention through vaccination crucial.\n\n### **What to Do If You\u2019re Bitten by a Dog**\n1. **Wash the Wound:** Immediately clean the bite area with soap and water.\n2. **Seek Medical Attention:** Consult a healthcare professional promptly, especially if the dog's rabies vaccination status is unknown.\n3. **Report the Incident:** Notify local animal control or public health authorities so they can assess the risk and take appropriate action.\n\n### **Conclusion**\nRabies in dogs is preventable and relatively uncommon in regions with effective vaccination and control measures. Ensuring that your dog is vaccinated against rabies not only protects your pet but also contributes to public health and safety. If you have concerns about rabies or your pet's health, it's best to consult with a veterinarian or local health authorities.",
